Work has kept my mind busy, and absolutely exhausted. I still have a hard time waking up at 3:45 in the morning and heading to the chow hall by 4:15. For the last year and a half I'd been waking up between 9 and 10am with no alarm. It's helping though, because the last time I thought of counting my days left, I had 88 remaining. I've stopped talking to most people here, mostly as a result of my keeping busy. Some acquaintances have taken this incredibly personally and don't even acknowledge me when passing by in the halls. Fuck em anyway. Much like with high school, I won't be talking to 99% of these people when I get out anyway. There are a handfull I will though. The expected results of working there seem to be paying off already, or my body image is improving lol. Probably a bit of both. I have noticed on non-cardio days, I have a bit more stamina to carry on through the workouts, and while I do take small extra breaks between the ending sets of pushups, they're becoming less frequent, and I do every single one now. 100% completion. My arms look alright. Would like them a little bigger to compensate for my midsection...or I'd like to shed some more of the fat off my midsection to look more proportionate with my arms lol. Probably a bit of both again. Whoever sent me the crossword puzzle book, thank you! Not gonna lie, I cheated on the first 10, less and less with each one, but im on puzzle #11 now and I haven't looked at the answers in the back a single time yet. A friend said to me awhile ago I should try re-reading some of my books. I thought that was weird, but I started bringing my copy of The Fountainhead to work and have been enjoying it more this time around. And that reminds me, that book, of how much yall have taken care of me in here. My friends, supporters, all of yall. You've made my time easy peasy, and when I'm reminded of how well taken care of I am in here, it makes my stresses seem silly. Yeah, 78 more days, but the last 600-and-something have been a cakewalk (for the most part). There's a lot of people in here who get forgotten about in here. Its sad. I think I might start writing my memoir again too. I stopped it awhile ago because it seemed like a stupid, repetitive thing to write about since I'm sure half the J6ers are all writing their own (BOOOORRIIIING) but I realized I was writing about an ordeal that I hadn't yet gotten through. That was in April or May last year I stopped writing, and now that I'm near the end of my time, I think I'll pick it back up. Thanks for reading. Thanks for supporting me. I'll be out soon, a changed man, but not the way the feds were hoping for lol! Love yall. miss yall. -Flex Luthor

UPDATE: THE FINAL DAYS Just waiting. Waiting... I used up all my phone minutes almost 2 weeks ago, thinking I'd be out by now and I wouldn't need to stretch em out lol. I have 3 minutes left, in case I'm called for immediate release and I gotta call my mom to come get me. I revalidate on Saturday, but man...I really hope I'm gone before that haha Knowing you're going home is typically a very stressful thing in here. Your time slows down, you have less and less tolerance for the people around you that you see every single day, you become irritable, impatient, you stare at the clock a lot more. It's even worse when you know you're leaving "soon", but don't have an exact day. Every time you hear the guard's keys jingle or the counselor's door open, I keep thinking "OH SHIT WHAT IF ITS EARLY RELEASE TIME RIGHT FUCKING NOW AND THEY'RE COMING FOR ME". I'd imagine a dog wanting to go outside feels the exact same way every time a person gets off the couch. My lawyer filed the motion this morning. Hopefully I'll hear something this week. I'm bored to death of everything. Just like when I first came in, I keep having dreams of being in the free and getting out; My mind has already left here. I think I'll take 2-4 days when I leave here to just enjoy the freedom. Not getting drunk or anything, but driving around and just being able to move. I miss driving so damn much. I think I'll take my dog to a park or two on my 2nd day. Then take him home, go to Chili's, and get a tripple dipper (or a big mouth burger with the blossom petals instead of fries) and a Blue Moon with a wedge of orange. Restring my guitar, see if my amp still works too and do some shredding. Play some pool with my folks if they're still able to. Listen to music I haven't been able to hear in a year and a half. See a few friends that night. This is my first day of freedom plan. Then I gotta hit the ground running working. Been out of work for too long lol. I'll update my channel myself once I get out. I don't think I'll delete it, I'm really interested in seeing a whole year and a half of documenting some of my experiences in here, and of course adding to them with all the shit I didn't feel I should say on this computer lol. Love yall. See yall soon. Can't wait for some freedom! -Prison Nicky

Idk if my lawyer ever filed anything either, I'm trying to be patient. Stress eating has hit me hard again, and I gotta stop leaning on sweets for comfort. I took most of last week off from working out because I was sick, but I figured my body could use the break from excercise anyway. Still feeling beefy, might get some pics done this weekend. Yall help me out a ton. Ansley, I've been getting the Epoch Times now, just got my 3rd issue. Thank you! The extra on commissary will help me out tomorrow too, thank you! All my clothes I bought a year ago are pretty worn out. It doesn't help that there's only 1 laundry day a week here, but there's hardly enough room in your locker for 3-4 changes of clothes, so shower washing them and wringing them out to dry (because we lack places to hang our stuff to dry) has left most of the elastic on my stuff just absolutely obliterated. I'm ready to get outta here: Got a job lined up already that'll pay good enough to take care of me, my family, and help out other J6ers. Affordable Piston Ar Part 2 First off, zeroing this rifle went very quickly, without a bore sight I was on paper at 25 yards, made some small adjustments and went to 50 then 100 yards very quickly. Accuracy was acceptable as most groups measured right at an inch. Although I prefer sub MOA across the board to get 1‚Äù at 100 with an ‚Äúaffordable‚Äù rifle right out of the box is more than adequate. I went out to 200 and dialed in even tighter, this is actually the range that AR‚Äôs are meant to zeroed for use with ballistic reticles that are now very common. Reliability was great, I had zero failures even with cheap steel cased ammo. Which is expected from a piston. The scope also impressed me for the money, even on 8 magnification the glass was remarkably clear and the FOV was enormous considering. The next test will be torture, running 10 mags nonstop and throwing it around onto the dirt, into the truck bed etc and seeing if we hold zero with no malfunctions So far though this rifle is outperforming ANY AK, let‚Äôs see if I can force it to fail

Affordable Piston AR When discussing AR vs AK, most who choose the AK do so because of the designs inherent reliability due to its piston operating system. They are willing to sacrifice range and modularity in favor of the piston‚Äôs reliability and AK‚Äôs loose manufacturing tolerances. Piston AR‚Äôs bridge that gap but most complain about their high price and limited availability. This series covers the components and impressions of an affordable option vs higher end LMT, HK, LWRC and other piston AR‚Äôs designed to be deployed immediately onto the battlefield. Aero precision lower with SOPMOD stock : $299 Adams Arms 5.56 upper with magpul fore end: $599 Vortex Strike Eagle with one piece mount 1-8x24mm LVPO: $299 While this totals to around $1200 it is less than half of what the aforementioned rifles would cost with no optics so it‚Äôs affordable in comparison. There is no $500 complete piston that‚Äôs worth a damn. Initial impressions: all the components fit together nicely right out of their boxes, the scope was easy to mount and level, it feels like a quality weapon overall I‚Äôll discuss performance in the next post

J6 Prison Update Day 401 Well, I think its 401. Jan 10th was 365. Who cares!? Today I learned an important lesson (again) while doing cardio today. Originally I had planned to take this week off from doing anything regarding upper body, as to avoid further pain in my shoulders. Monday I went outside for pushups anyway. We did our usual, but I dropped the number to 10s: 10 straight pushups, 10 incline, and 10 decline, and halfway through went up to sets of 12 each, but also on the 2nd half of each set doing them with a 1 second pause at the bottom and at the top. I had no pain in my shoulders. Today we went out and instead of 357's, we did burpees; 100 single pump to start, see-saw. I decided to do 7 or 8, but take a small break before the next 10. No pain in the shoulders. Next we did 1the same thing, but with the jump at the end of each. I did 80%, and again, had no pain in the shoulders. We did 10 down see-saw(10, then 9, then 8, then 7, and so on) and I kept my number just a smidge under the usual, and then we did 10 UP, I did me the same way. No shoulder pains. What I learned was I need to stop trying to rush to my goal. This isn't a race, and I don't have a deadline to reach whatever goal or limitation I haven't even set, other than just keeping up with our leader. Where many, myself included, keep setting unrealistic standards and just give up when they can't reach it, I instead tried to shortcut it and just force my way to that level, which is ALSO not the right way lol. I'll continue to push it to 100%...and maybe a smidge more...but there's no hurry, and I need to stop pushing myself to injury. I'm hoping when I get out that some of you will want to join me in these kinds of workouts if you aren't already active. I've learned how to condition my body to do things I never thought I'd be capable of, and in such a short frame of time I didn't think was possible either. In acheiving this, I can help anyone else interested in doing the same. There's no excuse for being fat, weak, and unhealthy in the mind, body, and spirit. I hope I'm not coming off cocky or anything, but I'm at a level of inner peace I've never had before, and in knowing this joy, I'd be a real selfish jerk to try not to share this with others. Anywho, yesterday was Ash Wednesday. Bishop Michael came to do our service yesterday, and his delivery is a little refreshing. For lent, I'm going to give up swearing. If profanity is the sign of a weak mind, then I will solidify mine without resorting to weaker vocabulary. I've already made a deal with my celly; for every 3 times I use profanity around him, I'm gonna owe him my dinner for that night. That should be plenty of motivation to stick with my goal lol. I checked with my case manager to see if regional has put in my change of district this week....they haven't. Ah well, praying for next week so I can be put in for the halfway house. Nothing else really going on. Love yall. Miss yall. -Nicky

Homemade French Bread ‚Ä¢ 2 ¬º cups warm water around 110¬∞F ‚Ä¢ 1 ¬Ω tbsp granulated sugar ‚Ä¢ 1 tbsp active dry yeast ‚Ä¢ 2 tsp table salt ‚Ä¢ 2 tbsp vegetable oil or olive oil ‚Ä¢5-6 cups all-purpose or bread flour scooped & leveled ‚Ä¢1 egg beaten with 1 tsp cold water ‚Ä¢ Melted salted butter (optional) Combine warm water, sugar & yeast; let yeast proof for 5-10 mins. Add salt, oil & 3 cups of flour. Stir until dough starts to combine. Gradually add remaining flour until tacky. Knead for 3 mins; rest for 5 mins. Knead again for 2 mins. Let dough rise for an hour. Divide into 2 parts. Pat 1 part into a 9x13 rectangle, roll into a cylinder, and place on a parchment-lined baking sheet. Repeat for 2nd part. Cover with plastic wrap; let rise for 30 mins. Preheat oven to 375¬∞F. Before putting the loaves in oven, brush with egg wash & make gashes on top. Toss 4 ice cubes on the oven floor, and bake for 25 mins until golden. Still at $800 it‚Äôs not a budget or a higher end carbine In the next review we will see how it does at 100 yards suppressed and run a mixed mag of hollow points and FMJ of all kinds of brands to see if we can get it malfunction Henry Homesteader 9mm/ Glock Mag Fit/Finish/Quality 8/10 Accuracy 8/10 Reliability 10/10 Functionality/Practicality 10/10 Price/Value 8/10

Henry Homesteader Review Part 2 In the first part of this review series we mostly focused on first impressions and fit/finish/physical quality as well as potential uses for the 9mm semi auto carbine from Henry In this portion I going to tell you about my experience shooting, handling, and customizing this carbine. So my few outings with the homesteader were using the supplied factory 5 and 10 mags; both worked perfectly and looked great in the gun. If you prefer the traditional look and don‚Äôt need more than ten rounds at a time then stick with this configuration because you won‚Äôt like how it looks with the Glock mag well. I shot with the stock irons which is a simple post and peep sight. I shot beer cans at 25-50 yards which was difficult with the sights at 50 because the sight post obscures the target. It was evident that the weapon itself was capable of greater accuracy than the sights in my hands. I prefer optics over irons on long guns always so I decided to put a scope on it. I chose a trijicon 3x9-40 accupoint that is a work horse of a scope I‚Äôve used on many rifles. I‚Äôm not crazy about the vortex rings I used and will switch to Trijicon rings later. The recoil of 9mm in this carbine is non-existent so I‚Äôm not really worried about the rings rattling loose. I will say that I was shocked to find the factory‚Äôs supplied and mounted rail to be loose when I took it shoot, it rattled very slightly but enough to change POI(point of impact) so I tightened it down in the field without lock tite. Once I have the trijicon rings on hand I‚Äôll lock tite everything. The homesteader came to zero quickly with little fuss it was shooting pretty far to the right (stupid vortex rings) and a little low. You‚Äôll see in the picture how far I had to move up and left. Once I had it hitting the bullseye consistently I shot another 100 rounds ringing steel, all at 50 yards from various positions. While this carbine is capable of 100 yard shots with this scope I didn‚Äôt bother because I was having so much fun at 50.

Prison Update Day 387 So, after talking with several convicts in here, I've noticed most of them have old flames they still communicate with, even in prison. My neighbor mentioned speaking with an ex on the phone and I told him I found that odd. He was puzzled and asked why I DON'T communicate with any of my exs, to which I replied "Doesn't everyone end a relationship like I do? Get into a shouting match, destroy each other with words, burn the bridge and walk away!". I was told that in fact THIS was odd. Idk. I noticed a smidge of performance loss with this new diet, or it's strain from doing extra on Saturday. I've decided to start doing 200 pushups on Saturdays, and hopefully this Sunday I'll be able to another 200, and eventually just do 200 pushups every day on top of the weekday workouts. As my time is getting shorter in here (No, I still don't have an outdate, I just know it'll be June or earlier) I worry about being able to stay motivated and push myself past my limits WITHOUT having my workout car. If I'm able to bring myself to do 200 pushups a day extra, by myself, I think that might help. I don't know what kind of working out I'll be doing when I get out, I'm sure it'll be with weights though. I don't think I know anyone around that'd wanna do this kinda stuff anyway. Everyone (that works out) wants to move the weights. I cheated a couple times...or at least I only remember cheating a couple times...and I went up 5lbs and 2% body fat. Now, the device we use to measure looks kinda cheap; It's shaped like a playstation controller, you hold it out straight and touch metal contacts on it. I don't know how reliable it is really...but I do look a smidge fatter. The new diet will help with this. 1500 calories a day. I'm gonna look right when I get out or die trying to dammit! lol I've finished my books. Angels in Iron was absolutely badass. Never thought I'd like historical fiction. It's about the Christian Knights of St Johns Hospitallers fighting off the Muslim invasion of Sultan Suleiman in Malta in the 1500s. Loved it. Some great characters in it. The author did his research on the whole thing, so I wonder how accurate a few of the characters are in it and how many of them were real. Children of Time was great. Excellent sci-fi. I wont get into what its about, you have the internet, look it up! I loved it. If anyone would...idk...wanna send me the sequel, I'd appreciate it lol. I JUST finished In The Foreign Legion by Erwin Ross. The author joins the French Foreign Legion in 1905 without telling anyone and realizes it was a huge mistake. Legionares were paid 2% what an American soldier was paid at the time and 4% what an English soldier was. They made enough money to buy 2 and a half bottles of shitty wine every week, or one pouch of tobacco. They were essentially slaves and were only fed twice a day, soup and bread, every day. Wild. Anyways, I'm about to start The Hoffman Process, but I'm sure it's just another shitty self help book. Psh. I got no news other than my weight gain. Love yall, see yall soon! (Happy now, Kodiak?) -Nicky the Fatso

Prison Update Day 380 I've mastered burpees. Tuesday we did 100 double pump burpees, 2 at a time, see-saw. We then did another 100 single pump the same way. We might've done more, I don't really remember. Every time we do legs, there's a point we reach doing calves where there's a sharp pain, then they go numb and you can do another 40-50. I reached a similar point in the burpees; About halfway through the 2nd hundo I reached a mental calmness and didn't acknowledge my breathing, the strain in my chest, or the inflammation in my shoulder. For the first time in the group, I kept up with X doing cardio where everyone kept taking small breaks and losing rhythm. I think my lungs have fully recovered from years of smoking, and I've stopped coughing, wheezing, and hacking up gack. My goal before I leave in a few months is to get to 15-17% body fat. Finally being able to breathe on Tuesdays and Thursdays cardio will help me get there a little quicker and burn more. Only thing stopping me is this bitch ass shoulder muscle. I gotta find something for inflammation, I think. I've finally written 2 letters in reply, only 8 more to go lol. Idk why I can't sit there and focus on writing. Sitting at a keyboard still feels way more natural to me. Ah well. I'll throw some music on and crank em out. Downloaded Tom's Diner by Suzanne Vega, but not the version with the 90's dance hiphop beat. Got some new Chromeo too. Personal Effects is killer, so is (I Don't Need A) New Girl. Got some Tom Waits as well. Sadly, they don't have Christmas Card From A Hooker In Minneapolis. Thank you to everyone that's been keeping me fed. The extra protein I get from commissary helps a ton, especially when everything they serve here is loaded with carbs. I'm definitely gonna need some new socks and underwear next month, as everything I have is loaded with holes. We only have 1 laundry day a week and we're not allowed to do laundry on the unit, so I wash my workout stuff in the shower with me, and wringing that stuff out stretches the shit outta everything, but again, not allowed to have laundry hanging anywhere. C'est la BOP. Did I mention I can't wait to go home xD My new diet, to try and get to 15-17% while I'm here, is skipping both breakfast (hot garbage) and lunch, my first meal is a protein bowl of brown rice, soy taco mix, and mackerel post workout, and I'll eat a second for dinner if what they're serving is garbage (which tonight definitely is). The goal is only consuming enough carbs to restore the glycogen in my muscles and re-upping calories with a deficit of at least 800-900 daily. I'm on day 3, and I haven't noticed any dip in my daily energy, nor my performance in the workout. Will adjust it if I NEED to. I'm halfway doing this diet out of spite. Love you all. See you all soon! -Nick

Random Pieces of Advice to Aspiring and New Homesteaders: 1. Don't underestimate the costs and stresses of building on raw land. Here is a voice message I discussed the considerations of raw land ‚Äî https://t.me/BeginnerHomesteader/1363 . Most of the desperately unhappy homesteaders I've known are thus because of things related to building on raw land. I also know people who have been happy doing it, but they're the minority in my experience. 2. Live as close to a convenient city as you can. After a number of moves, we made 45 minutes the max travel time. This 45 minutes is still a big social barrier. If you live this far out, you have to have the mindset that adding 1.5 hours or more to every activity isn't a problem. You have to have a reliable vehicle and a big gas budget. 3. Think about who you are ‚Äî not your fantasy self. Align your location, lifestyle, and choices with who you actually are ‚Äî not your fav youtube homesteader. 4. Know that RVs are poorly made and definitely not made for full time living. 5. There's a sweet spot between too small and too big in a house. In our experiences, too small is way more stressful than too big. 6. A good rule of thumb is that every single homestead thing takes twice as long and twice as much money to do as budgeted. 7. Put one foot in front of another without focusing on finishing the tasks. 8. Try things out and be willing to let things go ‚Äî especially with livestock. We kept pigs one year. It was pretty sucky. But we learned a lot. We will take these lessons and try again. We kept rabbits. We'll only keep them again in case of dire necessity. We kept a milk cow. We realized the importance of pasture quality ‚Äî as well as the level of structure a milk cow requires. We might do it again some day. Chickens are awesome. Turkeys, too. Shearing sheep... not so much. Be flexible. 9. Make sure to schedule fun in. The work will never never never be all done. 10. Keep tweaking, learning, and trying. Another year of gardening awaits. We're hopeful this is the year we succeed ü§™ 11. Take time to make things beautiful. It usually doesn't take much time. The crabbiest homesteaders I know are the ones who view every single thing in purely utilitarian way. Beauty is a manifestation of God. 12. Most people think that you need a ton of land. There are people with amazing homesteads on just a few acres. The more land you have, the more maintenance you have. Big land really requires a tractor. 13. A spring makes winter livestock keeping so much easier if your animals have access to the spring. 14. Your neighbors are a big impact on your life. Perhaps even more so than living in a town. 15. Don't move to a climate you're unfamiliar with. If you do, definitely rent for a year. 16. know that selling rural land/homestead can take years. Purchase yours accordingly.

Prison Update Day 356 Happy New Year! This time last year I was stressing pretty hard about getting locked up, all of my free time went to drinking, snorting and stressing all the way to my self surrender. Looking back now, idk if I really hid the stress well or not. Almost a whole year in, and the progress I've made on myself is huge. God has a funny way of teaching you the lessons you want to learn, and its never the easy way. Years ago I wanted to get stronger physically, mentally, and spiritually. I knew though, that with asking for God to help me with these things, he'd present me with an ordeal to overcome. Shortly after thinking about this, the capitol bullshit happened and after 2 stressful years of pretrial supervision, I wound up here with what I essentially asked for. If I had somehow miraculously been one of the 2% that beat the charges the federal government gives them, I probably would have gone back to wasting time, being a fat, lazy piece of shit. I keep forgetting what I'm even typing about. I'm drained after pushups today. 15 regular perfet form pushups, 15 incline, and 15 decline. 10 sets, 450 pushups, and a burnout of 24 at the end. Damn good way to start a new year, although I'm not one of those "new year resolution" goofballs; Just do better now dummy! A year ago I never thought I'd be able to go as hard as I do now. My body and mind feel off if I don't do the workouts now. I'm confident I wont fall back into shitty, seditary life habbits like before. I'm ready to get outta here and make up for the lost time in here and all the years I wasted before this legal bullshit too...Just gotta lose some more of this gut before I leave here lol. I think another 10-15lbs of fat and I'll be comfortable. I don't have much else to say. My brain's tired, gotta finish a drawing I've been working on in the "rubber hose" cartoon style. Probably get that finished this week. Love you all. Miss you all. Can't wait to get out of this shithole. -Nick

Update Day 351 We got a Christmas bag full of free snacks on Thursday; 2 bags of TGI Fridays potato skin chips 1 pack of Coconut Macaroons (artifically flavored, of course) A brownie 1 10 pack of fruit punch mixes A small pack of strawberry cream duplex cookies some other shit and the best item, a bag of Snyder's Honey Mustard and Onion pretzel bites. I've been craving these for a year now. I traded half my holliday bag for others pretzels. WHAT A TREAT! Christmas lunch/dinner was pretty damn pathetic. Everyone's own personal Cornish hen sounds great in theory, but the tiny bones covered in bird skin we were served made the pigeons and squirrels outside look appetizing. Squirrel stew was definitely a dish we considered, little tree rats looking extra plump around winter. The sides with the meal were great, even the mini pecan pie, but the "bird" we got was cooked for an unnecessary extra 12 hours. It looked like they took the skin off, removed the meat from the bones, and put the skin back on. Shit looked like Imhotep from The Mummy starring Brendan Frascher and Oded Fahr (however their names are spelt). Prison Update Day 328 (sad news) Well, I waited to make this update in hope I'd have better news regarding the FSA bulletin that went out, but sadly I don't. It doesn't appear that the way the bulletin explains how time credits will be applied is going to be honored, sadly, regardless of a staff member confirming it WOULD. Again, just how it appears. Also, not speaking poorly of the staff. Still waiting on that sentencing ammendment though, so hopefully that'll reduce my time a bit. Praying for that halfway house in April. We did our pushup routine we've been on for the last few weeks, but instead of explosions, we did ALL the pushups with perfect form, 1 second up and 1 second down. I was on sets of 15, so 15 normal, 15 incline, and 15 decline. I THINK I put in 8 sets before I had to drop to 10....then 5 on the following lol. Just did the math, and I did over 400 puhups. Feels good. I didn't lose my form and rely on my shoulders either. Last Thursday I set a new personal record. We did 3-5-7s, and I haven't done those since (I believe) my 2nd month working out. 3 half-burpees, 5 Mike Tysons, 7 crawl-outs. I did 26 sets, and I was going to push to 30, but others quit before I did. 78 half-burpees, 130 Mike Tysons, and 182 crawl-outs (I think I did that math right (fuck it, it's right enough!)) I think June was my second month doing this, and when we did 3-5-7s then, I think I was doing 3-4-5s and only made it to 15 sets lol. Probably had to swap the crawl-outs for regular pushups too. ATX is our sensei, showing us how to overcome our limits we put on ourselves, and calm the storm in our minds. I don't know if I have a goal for what I want to look like, but my mind and body are getting stronger for sure. The entire compound hasn't had recreation in 8 days now, and it's rumored we wont get it again til February. Something about needing metal detectors at the gate. Idk. It's bullshit, and I would imagine is going to affect the mental health of many in here not being outside. It sucks for me, since I can't check out a guitar again, and the guitar teacher is dying of cancer so by the time we get rec back, he might already be dead or under some kind of intensive care. I was just nailing the riff for Dashboard by Modest Mouse too. Just awful. There's some special holiday items for sale at comissary that'll only be here for this month. They also upped our spend limits to $410 this month only. If anybody wants to bless me and my books with some extra dough ;D I'd appreciate it! I was kinda getting down on the new with the FSA shit, but I'm over it. I'll get out whenever I get out. I'm learning self discipline in here. Im improving the trifecta of one's self: Body, Mind, and Soul. Although I can't weigh myself right now with the scales being at recreation, I'm still going hard as fuck on the diet. I'm going doubly as hard on the workouts. I've been going to RCIA at Mass every Sunday. I'm improving every day while I watch others in here at a stand still. I hope you all reading this are doing well also. Love you all. Miss you all. -Nick

When you look at charts and graphs every day you use that math" me:"I don't look at charts and graphs every day, the fuck are you talking about? In 1928, a figure known as the Ice Man could be seen delivering a 25-pound ice block in Houston, Texas. This snapshot reflects a time when the ice trade was a highly profitable industry, primarily during the 19th and early 20th centuries. Ice was harvested from natural sources such as ponds and streams and then transported via railroads or ships to various destinations worldwide. An intricate network of ice wagons was responsible for the final distribution of this valuable commodity. The roots of this industry can be traced back to 1806 when Frederic Tudor, also known as the Ice King, initiated the ice trade in New England by shipping ice to his affluent clientele in the Caribbean. Over the years, his enterprise expanded to encompass regions like Cuba and the southern United States. Eventually, ice was being shipped to destinations as far-flung as India, Australia, China, and South America. At the zenith of the ice trade, this sector in the United States employed a staggering 90,000 individuals and relied on the labor of 25,000 horses. The demand for ice experienced a notable upswing during World War I. However, once the war concluded, the ice trade saw a precipitous decline due to the advent of refrigeration cooling systems. By the 1930s, modern refrigerators began to gain prevalence in households, and by the 1950s, they had become nearly ubiquitous in both the United States and Europe. This technological advancement rendered the ice trade largely obsolete. Just the memory of this guy could beat my ass. @MurderTheMedia

Prison Update Day 295 Monday's pushups were great. Not sure what you'd call these, but we did pushups with our feet on the window sill behind us, kinda like an incline benchpress. I alternated between sets of 12 regular, 2 second good-form pushups, and sets of 10 inclines. Definitely feeling that soreness on the top of my pecs. I went down to the legal library today to talk to my buddy that's helping me with the sentencing ammendment stuff, and he's swamped with helping people. I'm going to attempt to get in touch with my public defender from this case to see if he'll file for the adjustment instead. I've been an exemplary "adult in custody", been doing all the programming and taking classes, working on getting my GED. Shouldn't be any reason to deny me the time adjustment. I did the math, and with a year of halfway house, AND with my sentence adjusted, I should be outta here no later than April. Without the adjustment, it might be August - October next year. Please pray for Ochs and I, that we may be granted a little more mercy on our sentences. I've been eating like shit the last couple days, and I've noticed that my dieting tends to have a rubber band effect when I jump in too hard to extreme dieting, always rebounding hard. So....my theory is with eating horribly the last couple days, ESPECIALLY last night, my feelings of sickness and stomach achedness should rubber band me back into eating healthy. My weight hasn't moved in a week. I'm stuck at 209 lbs. I hope throwing this dietary curveball will put my metabolism in check. 24 lbs till I reach my goal. Big thanks to my local boys, and big thanks to Ansley, for getting me some commissary funds. I think I'm covered for next month. That's about it for me. I've just been practicing guitar, excercising, watching the world series (GO DIAMONDBACKS!) and pointlessly stressing over the sentencing ammendment stuff, which I shouldn't; I'll get out of here when I get out of here. Love you all. Miss you all. -Nick

For example: You go out there with a group of people, and between the bullshitting and swapping weights on the bars and all that, you're probably getting a 2-3 minute break between sets. Ours is a little different. We don't have time to really talk in between doing anything in our workout, because we don't leave time for bullshitting. We don't have weights to adjust. We have a lot to fit into a workout in the 90 minutes we do. For example, yesterday's workout: First 30 minutes, we did: -5 minutes of stretching -3 minute plank, 1 minute side plank on each side, then back to a 2 minute plank -100 leg lifts (Legs straight, lift them towards your head, touch the wall behind you. Legs don't touch the ground) -100 bicycles -3 minutes alternating straight legs in 12 o'clock, 11 o'clock, and 9:30 positions, 10 seconds each position. -100 V crunches Then after our 30 minutes of core, we did 300 burpees in 3 sets, seesaw (2 people burpee, then when they're done the other 2 people burpee, alternating) -100 3 pump burpees -100 2 pump burpees -100 1 pump burpees I'm seeing some quick results from all this, my strength is increasing, my ability to breathe through working out is improving, my body is looking better. No clue what kind of calories are being burnt each day, im sure Tuesday and Thursday cardio is burning more, but idk. My body is sore almost all the time, and I love it. I feel off when it isn't sore, as I didn't get enough of a workout. I go hard enough though, now, that even on Saturday and Sunday when I don't workout, im sore through the weekend. I may start doing 30 minutes on the reclined bike downstairs on those days, idk. I really enjoy resting and napping too lol. My tailbone is hurting from doing the core workouts on the hard floor 5 days a week. I have no ass to help. The DeCarlo's are an assless clan. Not much else to update. Love you all, miss you all -Nick AKA BigBeef AKA No-Ass Nicky

Big Beef's Prison Update: Day 179 Im approaching the 6 month mark, 1 more week til. I re-did the math, this time correctly and with help, on when I can expect to get out of here. 4 year sentence puts me at January 10th 2027 7 months good time brought it to June 10th 2026 Here's where it gets tricky though, with FSA and how time credits are earned over time passed while programming, by the end of the year I'll have earned 4 months off from completing 1 year (10 days off per month) Then on the 2nd year I start earning 15 days off per month. 1 year down, with my 7 months good time and 4 months FSA time credits: February 10th 2026 (roughly) Halfway house is given to people with 9-12 months to the door typically, which is something else to consider. By September of next year, I'll have earned 8 months off with FSA, combined with 7 months good time and (im hoping) a year of halfway house, I could be leaving prison by September 2024 for halfway house or home confinement. The workouts with my barber leading the group are starting to pay off, as Im keeping up on most excercises and surpassing others in a few routines too. Today: 2 minute plank, into 1 minute plank on each side, then back to 2 minute plank. Then on our backs: 25 reverse crunches, then 25 bicycles, then 50 reverse crunches into scissors(?), each set done without feet touching the ground. we did that for 30 minutes, then went into sets of 8 pushups, going 5 seconds up then 5 seconds down. I couldn't keep up on the pushups and had to go to my knees again, but I kept up with planking and crunches (and outlasted a few others), so I guess I have a good core. Just gotta shed this extra 40lbs off and keep working on arms. Cheated horribly over the weekend with dieting. Ate a banana moonpie and covered it in peanut butter. Had some cookies too. As much as Chad will be missed after he leaves this week for camp, at least he wont be here to pressure me into cheating with him lol. I haven't been doing Bible study in the last 2 weeks. It's too hard to keep up with people reading other translations from what im reading, and there's too much hootin an hollerin going on around us to focus. I'm gonna start reading a couple chapters a day on my own instead. Gonna rent The Batman tonight and watch it with my buddy Owens. Got our hands on a headphone splitter. Didn't get a visit from my parents last weekend. I called my mom, and my dad, on top of losing his vision, is starting to get loopy; Talking about and to people that aren't there, incoherent ramblings, other typical stuff that are signs of bad stuff to come. I hope it doesn't hit him this soon. Alzheimers runs on both sides of the family, and I've heard diabettes makes all that stuff worse. Praying he's still himself when I get out. Not much else to report on, except getting names mixed up on my last update (sorry Jeanne!) Love you all, miss you all. Nick AKA Dick NeCarlo AKA Big Beef AKA Threat Kavenaugh

cleaned_message: Canning corn Start by boiling the corn on the cob for 5 minutes, then move the corn to a pot of cold ice water for 5 minutes. Cut the corn off of the cob and pack into clean jars. Cover with the cooking water, leaving 1 inch headspace. Add 1/2 tsp of canning salt for pints and 1 tsp for quarts. Place jars into warm water in the pressure canner. Then fill jars with boiling water, leaving 1 inch of headspace. Clear air bubbles. Wipe jar rims clean and place lids - seal hand tight. Process pints for 55 mins or quarts for an hour and 25 mins, adjust for altitude. Using canning tongs, remove the jars from the canner to a towel to cool. When done, remove the rings. @BearToothBayou

Yesterday I ran out of diesel fuel while bush hogging on my tractor. When I filled the tank and tried to start it again, it wouldn't start. After doing a bit of internet research I realised that running a diesel engine out of fuel sucks air into the fuel lines, which is a major problem, and I would have to take the tractor apart and drain fuel lines to fix it. I called my neighbour to help, who is a 60 year old farmer. He brought an old rag with him and some petrol. I asked what he was going to do with it. He told me to hop on and start cranking the engine. While I was cranking, he took the air filter cap off and held the petrol-soaked rag to the air intake. To my amazement, the engine started firing on the petrol fumes. After a few seconds, it had fired enough to suck fuel back through the fuel lines again and started running on diesel. We didn't have to take apart anything or drain any fuel lines. The moral of the story is, good neighbours are better than the internet, and your average rural redneck farmer may not know how to code but he sure as heck knows tractor enginers.

However, some are bred specifically for one or the other. For instance, Leghorns are excellent egg chickens ‚Äî laying lots of eggs with less feed needs than other breeds ‚Äî but they never really get big enough to make them an ideal meat bird. Freedom Rangers are faster growing for earlier butchering ‚Äîbut also lay eggs . (without being totally weird like the Cornish Cross that has been engineered for meat to the point that you have to butcher them at a young age.) Heritage Breeds are dual purpose. Prison Update Day 51 I woke up with decent energy today, feeling refreshed too, which is odd for sleeping in the Greyhound station that has no AC and a...bunky(?) who moves around a lot at night. Grabbed coffee anyway, then mainline lunch right after was tilapia today. Always get great energy from fish. Either that, or my body is now used to the calorie deficit I've put in place. What a great day to go to rec! At least walk/jog around the track a few times... nope. Rec closed today. Every time I wanna go... Wasting my energy sitting in the hot library, fidgeting in my chair. My body WANTS to excercise right now dammit! I've been getting used to the daily convict life...but now it officially sucks worse. I'm not saying it got easier to not see my loved ones, lose my room, my chair, my desk, or my window with the perfect view. The lack of freedom to get this energy out and enjoy a beautiful day outside is more than an annoyance. I really wanted to check the scale again too, and my only option is the indoor rec area. I probably shouldn't be obsessing over that number anyway. Fuck it, I'll check it again in a few weeks. I don't need to replace that dopamine reward circuit I used to have for social media reactions with a new reward system for checking the scale. Another step in getting my mind where I want it too. What I'm still puzzled on is what I want to feel rewarded for doing and achieving. The only thing I can think of is getting out early, and 2 years (praying) is a little long to wait for that small satisfaction. I think I'll set my goal weight at 185. Im at 225 right now, and at 200 I'll increase my calories a smidge if I need to, because I'll start lifting again then as well. The stairs are getting easier to climb, I'm not winded at all after the 4th flight. I don't even crave sweets anymore at all, and I'm honestly kinda repulsed whenever I see people eating them...that, and seeing the amount of out-of-shape inmates here. Some have excuses: Missing a leg, needing a walker, handicapped in general. However, I'm seeing very young people in here disappear into their own obese masses. I'm gonna look towards the possitive stuff today: -I'm in an environment that's not only letting me diet, but making it easy for me (Couldn't be doing this without tuna packs from commissary, thank you all! <3) -My friend Irish fat-shames me and bullies me on my lack of muscle. Its very appreciated. -I can still come to the library to read and write in a quiet-ish place. -I've been a good boy, and I haven't lost any good boy time, praying I WONT lose any either. It's 2 years. I won't be in for nearly as long as most of these inmates. -I might be at a Camp in 6 months. Much more relaxed there, looser visitation rules and what not. -The Lord is always with me, and giving me the strength to overcome this mental Hell. Sorry for such a lengthy update. Haven't been able to write, and I don't have a chair to sit at the computer with in the unit. Love you all, -Ol Dick AKA DC AKA BigBeef AKA Threat Kavenaugh AKA BigManOnCampus69

Lightly butter a 12 inch dutch oven, cast iron skillet or baking pan. In a large mixing bowl combine the flour, salt, sugar, baking powder and cream of tartar. With a pastry cutter or fork, cut the butter into the flour mixture until the butter chunks break down slightly. If dough is tacky, knead in a little more flour to form a soft dough. Roll the dough out to about ¬æ to 1-inch thick. Cut with a biscuit cutter. Waiting The Year You will often hear "wait a year before you make any changes". Like a lot of good advice, this is hard to take. Homesteaders are an active lot! I lived in a neighborhood once that had a pair of nesting bald eagles that would return to the same tree every year. The new owners of that house had their "landscaping plan" executed before they moved in. If they had waited a year, they might have changed the plan of cutting down the eagles' tree. On the Homestead, waiting a year is even more important because your own life, not just the life of wild things trying to survive in a city, rely on the landscape. Much of the pasture that you see in this video was underwater yesterday because it is not infrequent that the river overruns its banks. We almost lost penned animals this time last year because we didn't know that fact. Rain, wind, sun, wildlife -- you need to know them and their seasonal ways for the successful building of your homestead. Wait the year ü§ç

Prison Update Day 15 #1 LENGTHY UPDATE TIME What a shit day starting out. I woke up to the intercom announcing "*unintelligible noise* COMMISSARY, COMMISSARY!" and thinking I was late to pick it up, I rushed out of bed, bolted out of my room and found out it was only Commissary WORKERS that were being called. Our setup is kinda odd, might be a lingering COVID protocol, but we turn in our commissary shopping lists on a Saturday, then the order is filled on Tuesday morning. So anyways, I have an appointment at 7:30am to go to the mail room, have to go to commissary and then after hauling my groceries back up 4 flights of stairs, run back down to the education department to inform them just HOW retarded I am and talk about the classes they're going to make me take. I go downstairs to the mailroom, to find out the Catechism (I think that's how its spellt) Mike Lasater (VP of Communications, MTMedia St Louis) sent me isn't allowed because it's a hard cover book, so I had the mail guy imediately return it to get my money back. Forgot my bag for Commissary. Up 4 flights of stairs back up to my room, see my creepy celly for a split second and bolt back down the stairs to commissary, stand there for an hour til my name is finally called. Throw my stuff in my bag, walk all the way back accross the courtyard, back up 4 flights of stairs, and start looking over my receipt....they didn't give me the shoes I ordered (I'm wearing loaner sneakers from the KAR) Got my coffee though, so I filled my mug with that Keefe brand instant prison coffee, run back down 4 flights of stairs just in time for my 9am appointment with the head of prison education....and she showed up 15 minutes late. My appointment ends at 9:30am, and I have 30 minutes to kill in that building before the next 10 minute move on the hour. I checked out Atlas Shrugged by Ayn Rand, because they didn't have her #1 book Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (or was it Willie Wonka?) Left my coffee mug at the library. Its gone. Gotta wait 2 more weeks for the next commissary to get a new one. What a shit morning @PrisonDick

Are you thinking "this summer, we'll build a coop and get some chickens"? Start now! You do NOT need a coop! We have raised hundreds of chickens from day old chicks and have never once started them "in a coop". Your number one concern with newly hatched chicks is keeping them warm. This is because a chick cannot regulate its body temperature for at least 6 weeks and it takes 3 months for them to get all of their feathers. Until then, they need to be kept warm. All you need is an enclosure and a heat lamp. Any 4 sided building that blocks the wind, e.g. garage, shed, playhouse, unused room in your house + heat lamp + box/corral for the chicks. An extra large Sterilite tote works great and is easy to clean out bedding. Once they get bigger, an extra large dog cage can be used. Anything that keeps them enclosed. Chickens start laying at about 6 months old. Get chicks now and you won't want or need a coop until April at the earliest. And you'll have laying chickens this summer!

Preparing Livestock for Winter Straw and hay serve all our needs for keeping our animals warm. We have open air wired coops. This is fantastic in the summer for fresh air, sunshine, and livestock health. They're also easy to winterize with stacked straw bale walls. Straw bale walls keep the wind out and the livestock's warmth in. As the weather warms up, we dismantle them and use the straw throughout the homestead. A thick layer of hay or straw on the ground works in much the same way to insulate them‚Äî and also keeps them dry. Tarps ‚Äî tarps work to keep the wind out. But they do not work as insulators. Tarps are a lot less expensive than straw bale walls. Surely rope some tarps up if you don't have bales.
